    <title>Senate passes the Kids Online Safety Act</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="Photo collage of a photo of the US Capitol building with an image of the Constitution behind it." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/bUR8OnOg7eL38KgdkAGtclDaro4=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73491187/STK481_STK432_CONGRESS_GOVERNMENT_CIVRGINIA_C.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Image: Cath Virginia / The Verge; Getty Images&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="y2aNP2"&gt;The Senate passed the Kids Online Safety Act (KOSA) and the Children and Teens’ Online Privacy Protection Act (also known as COPPA 2.0), the first major internet bills meant to protect children to reach that milestone in two decades.&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;A legislative vehicle that included both KOSA and COPPA 2.0 passed 91–3. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="IgfN4a"&gt;Senate Majority Leader Chuck Schumer (D-NY) called it “a momentous day” in a speech ahead of the vote, saying that “the Senate keeps its promise to every parent who’s lost a child because of the risks of social media.” He called for the House to pass the bills “as soon as they can.”&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="s2QIy8"&gt;KOSA is a landmark piece of legislation that a persistent group of parent advocates played a key role in pushing forward — meeting with lawmakers, &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/2/1/24057460/senators-confront-meta-tiktok-snap-x-discord-ceos-kids-online-harm"&gt;showing...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
